	<td class="alt1">
	
		
			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				
				<strong>Tangled Web: Healing, HP inflation, Cleric Woes</strong>
			</div>
			<hr size="1" style="color:" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>The long ramblings from an old Druid...<br />
<br />
Does SOE have a definative plan to obsolete the broken Complete Heal spell?  How will the one dimensional Cleric class fit into EverQuest with the next few expansions and beyond?  Will healing roles be diversified and/or equalized for priests, and will we ever be rid of the CH rot?<br />
<br />
There is one answer, although the <i>question</i> is unclear.  HP's are rising, and sharply.  From a max of 125HP items in Luclin, to 200+ in PoP and with LDoN Augs, the result is undeniable.  But what problem is it solving?  Is this a direct and deliberate design to phase out CH?<br />
<br />
<b>Complete Heal</b><br />
There are two ways to make Complete Heal obsolete:<ol style="list-style-type: decimal"><li>Make a better heal</li><li>Make situational encounters</li></ol>And then, there is the false assumption:<br />
<b> 3.</b> Higher HP's will make Complete Heal obsolete.  This is blatently <b>FALSE!</b>  As long as CH is the largest heal, and has the best HP to Mana ratio it will remain the king of healing.<br />
<br />
The enjoyable answer lies in a combination of #1 and #2.  For instance:<br />
<b>Better Heal</b><ul><li>15k heal, 1200 mana, 5 second cast</li><li>7k heal, 1000 mana, 3 second cast</li><li>10k heal over time, 5 ticks, 500 mana, 2 second cast</li></ul><b>Situational Encounter</b><ul><li>Fast damage</li><li>Heavy damage</li><li>AE stun completely removing the CH rotation, or at least making it extremely risky</li><li>A short fight</li></ul>The point is a "Better" heal then CH doesn't have to be more mana efficient, but it absolutely does need to work best in the situational encounter.  Or else, CH will remain the achilles heel of the endgame.<br />
<br />
<b>Cleric Woes</b><br />
Recent <a href="http://forums.thedruidsgrove.org/showthread.php?s=&amp;threadid=5675&amp;perpage=15&amp;pagenumber=13" target="_blank">discussion</a> has brought to light the fact that Clerics have a death grip on Healing.  And in turn, Healing has a death grip on Clerics.  A conundrum, to be sure.  It appears as though Clerics hate this one dimensional attribute of their class, and yet, refuse to let it go for fear of being left without a purpose.  Read through it if you have time, it deals with everything from healing numbers, to healing balance, to boredom, to burnout rates, to stress (Stress! In a game!).<br />
<br />
<b>The melee Cleric</b><br />
SOE has realized the plight of Clerics to some extent.  The solution (or partial solution) of the melee Cleric has received mixed reviews.  Any fundamental change to a class sends ripples through the tangled web we call EverQuest balance.  "Why have a Paladin in the group if a Cleric can melee almost as well, plus Complete Heal at the same time?"<br />
<br />
Continuing along the lines of SOE giving Cleric melee options... How does one accomlish thus without infringing on Palidins, and other melee classes in general?<br />
<br />
<b>One answer is:</b> Make the Cleric <i>choose</i> between melee and healer.<br />
A line of spells could do this, available throughout Cleric levels:  A Self only melee buff that blanks out all spell gems for 1 or 2 minutes.<br />
<br />
All spell gems would refresh just as the buff wears off (but it can't be clicked off).  The buff would be balanced for decent dps, through haste, dexterity, possibly a damage shield, plus defensive capabilities through HP regen, increased AC, maybe also a HP component.<br />
<br />
<b>The solo cleric?</b><br />
Essentially, when a Cleric turns melee he/she has zero spell options.  Therefore, this would really only be viable while solo, since a Cleric in a group and raid setting depends on spells.  The line of Cleric proc'ing hammers would also have a significant purpose.<br />
<br />
<b>The ultimate goal</b><br />
EverQuest 2 appears to have it right:<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				EQII is being designed so that any character from a given archetype is equally effecient at performing the primary role of his/her archetype as any other class from the same branch.
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>Does that have any bearing on EverQuest?  Not necessarily.  The status quo of healing may continue to exist to the end of EQ's days, where the Cleric death-grip remains.  Is that healthy?  I don't think so.<br />
<br />
I feel something is about to happen, in one of the next 2 expansions.  If there's one commitment SOE has stuck to, it is that they will do whatever it takes to "ensure the health of the game", be it nerfs, sweeping changes to gameplay, or what have you.  Just how much longer EQ can go on in this current fasion regarding the healing game, I have no idea.  Time will tell.<br />
<br />
Wyte WorldKnot</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td class="alt2">
		<img class="inlineimg" src="images/tdg/statusicon/user_offline.gif" alt="Wyte is offline" border="0" />


		
		
		
		
